Stock Price Time Series Analysis

Derek Tang

4/26/2020

Executive Summary

In this report, we analyze and model a dataset consisting of stock prices across 4 years of trading days in order to predict prices for the first ten trading days in October 2019. The model we settle on is an ARMA(1, 1, 0) model with one autoregressive parameter aftern differencing. Ultimately, we find that our stock price is modelled quite well as a random walk along with a linear trend. Our forecasted values therefore are very close to a linear extrapolation of the trend line.

Exploratory Data Analysis

Before we begin modelling, we must first investigate our dataset and see if we can take any preprocessing steps. Plotting the original time series, we immediately notice that there is clear downward trend which looks quite linear at first glance. Additionally, we can see that the variance is heteroskedastic, with higher variances appearing at higher stock prices, which makes sense because price movements are typically analyzed as percent changes rather than absolute movement. The relationship between variance and mean lead me to pursue a log transformation to stabilize the variance.

Left: Time series plot of stock price data. Right: Time series plot of log transformed stock price data

We can see here that the variance now looks much more homoskedastic after the log transformation. Given that we are dealing with stock prices, one might guess that more dramatic price movements can be correlated to earnings reports, which come out at quarterly intervals, or perhaps other outside events (i.e. elections, Trump tweets, etc). Also, we notice that not all days have price data - weekends and holidays are excluded from the US trading calendar. This is something to note as it can create imperfect periods if we are looking to model seasonality in the data.

Models Considered

After considering the nature of stock price movements and the data itself, it was clear that in order to achieve stationarity I would have to remove the trend - I chose to do this by differencing the data. Additionally, in order to address possible seasonality within the data, I created a new dataset that filled in missing data on holidays with the average of the preceding and following trading days data points such that we can clearly define a “trading week” as five data points. I decided to model both this new dataset as well as the original dataset.

Time series plot of our differenced data

Model 1: Original Dataset

Our differenced data looks quite stable, so the next thing I did was to look at the sample acf and pacf plots across a large amount of lags to check for stationarity.

Sample ACF and PACF plot for our differenced data.

Based on these plots, it is hard to see a discernable pattern that would influence me towards picking a particular p or q for ARMA analysis and in fact the time series looks pretty close to stationary with only a few autocorrelations exceeding our 95% confidence interval which lead me to believe that this process could be modelled by few parameters. As no periodic pattern appears evident, I decided to use auto.arima() to help in parameter selection, and it chose an ARMA(1, 1, 0) model to fit the data.

In fact, when we use sarima() to fit the parameters of the model, we end up with a very small ar(1) coefficient which tells us that our data essentially resembles a random walk! This result is not too surprising in the context of our stock price, since we removed a linear trend with differencing leaving us with a process that is very close to stationary. I examined the plots from R’s sarima() function on our chosen model, and saw encouraging results. The acf of the residuals looks to be well contained in our confidence intervals, and the Ljung-Box test gives us no indication to reject our model as none of the p-values fall below the significance level.

Model 2: Cleaned Data

We now move to our new dataset, with substituted values. The goal of the substitution is to see if we can observe any clear seasonality on a monthly or quarterly basis.

Sample ACF and PACF plot for our differenced data.

However, after scrutinizing the acf and pacf plots, no discernable pattern appears, and for the most part the autocorrelations stay within the blue bands, however there are certainly a few outliers. Again, we turn to R’s auto.arima() function, which proposes the model ARMA(3, 1, 4) for the new data set. We will let this be our model on the new “cleaned” data set. After analyzing the outplut plots from fitting the data with sarima(), I concluded that the our model is quite reasonable, as the ACF of the residuals looks stationary and the Ljung-Box test does not have any points that would lead us to reject our model.

Model Comparison and Selection:

Now that we have two models, we need to decide which one best fits our data. While comparing the AIC and BIC for these two models does give us some information, these metrics are a little less useful since the models are working across two different data sets, and it is hard to quantify the differences in log-likelihood. Instead, I decided to use a couple of approaches to cross-validation. First, I used a cross validation scheme where the training set was created by iterating through each quarter and using data from the beginning to the current quarter. The next scheme I used picked 10 starting points at random from the most recent two years and took a years worth of data from that point on as the training set. The reason for having two schemes is because I wanted to explore how each model would fare taking into account sample size as well as recency. Below, we examine the performance of both models in each cross validation scheme.

Mean squared error for each model. Right: CV scheme 1 where each quarter represents a cumulative training set up until that quarter. Left: CV scheme 2 where each trial is independent and represents the MSE average of 10 randomly selected year long training sets within the last two years. Model 1 is shown in blue and Model 2 is shown in red.

Based on the first cross validation plot, it looks pretty clear that our more basic ARMA(1, 1, 0) model does a better job of lowering the mean squared error of the predictions. We can see that the error levels stay low and don’t variate as much as that of the ARMA(3, 1, 4) model. However, looking at our second cross validation scheme, the difference becomes a lot more negligible as the models perform similarly when averaged over 10 random training sets. We also observe slightly higher mean squared errors from our second cross validation scheme which uses smaller, more recent training sets. From this comparison, I think it makes the most sense to choose the ARMA(1, 1, 0) model accross the entire data set, as it performs favorably in the first cross validation scheme and has less parameters to fit, and thus has less of a tendency to overfit the data.

Results

I have selected the ARMA(1, 1, 0) model to generate predictions for the next 10 trading days, using the entirety of the original data set. From our sarima() function, we retrieve the estimate for our autoregressive parameter as well as our drift parameter (the slope for our trend):

Estimate Standard Error
ar1 -0.0070195 0.0290316
constant -0.0005406 0.0003233

We see that the autoregressive parameter is really very small, and with a confidence interval that includes 0. Below, we can see the predictions for the next ten trading days that our model produces as well as the error margins of the estimates.

Of course, to retrive our actual predictions, we must reverse the log transformation.
